The cerithioidean family 
Potamididae
shows a close association with mangroves. The great majority of its approximately 40 living species occur in mangrove habitats, where they are variously dependent upon the plants for shelter, as a substrate or for food (e.g. 
Houbrick 1984
, 
1991
; 
Plaziat 1984
; 
Glaubrecht 1997
; 
Willan 2013
; 
Reid 2014
). This ecological association has a long evolutionary history and is believed to have been characteristic of the family since its origin in the Tethyan realm during the Eocene (

Reid 
et al.
2008

).

The shells are not routinely decollate, although the very earliest whorls are always eroded. The spire profile of the adult shell is slightly convex (i.e. apical angle decreases with whorl number), but when the apex is well preserved the slender early whorls have a slightly concave profile (
Fig. 2D, P
). No protoconchs have been seen.

The sculpture of the shell consists of regular axial ribs, which become weak and irregular on the final whorl. In some populations of 

C. australiensis

there is evidence of damage by shell-crushing crabs; the final whorl is often broken away as far as a varix. The shell that is regrown following such damage is often smooth, lacking the axial ribs of undamaged shells. For both these reasons the number of axial ribs is counted on the penultimate whorl (i.e. from the point of junction with the outer apertural lip to one revolution back from this point). Spiral cords are visible on the earliest whorls, but become obsolete with growth. The periphery of the final whorl is considered to be the junction of the sides of the whorl and the shell base; it corresponds to the line of suture between successive whorls on the spire (not the point furthest from the axis of coiling). The periphery is marked by the outermost of two enlarged cords, which are part of the series of cords or threads counted on the base of the shell (clearly visible in 
Fig. 2P
). The outermost basal cord is usually just visible in the deep suture between succeeding whorls (
Fig. 2Q
). The shell is covered by a thick periostracum, which is marked by fine spiral microstriae, some of which bear short projections or bristles (
Fig. 3D
), but the periostracum is easily worn away and is rapidly lost from dead shells.

Distribution records and habitat.
The distribution records plotted on the map are based on personally verified museum collections and, in one case, on a reliable literature record. The records given in the text are of selected localities and range end-points and are not complete lists of material examined (these are available upon request and have been deposited in 
NHMUK
). Notes on habitat and ecology are based on personal observation unless otherwise acknowledged. Habitats are described with reference to the predominant genera of mangrove trees, which often show a characteristic zonation from seaward to landward sides in broad, undamaged mangrove stands (e.g. 
Macnae 1968
; 
Lozouet & Plaziat 2008
).

A statistical method was used to define species-level clusters in the COI tree. An ultrametric tree was generated in BEAST (v. 1.6.1, 
Drummond & Rambaut 2007
) and to find significant clusters within the tree the GMYC function from the SPLITS package (
Ezard, Fujisawa & Barraclough 2009
) in R (R 
Development Core Team 2009
) was applied (see detailed description by 

Reid 
et al
. 2013

). As further evidence for species delimitation, the uncorrected pairwise distances over all pairs of COI sequences were estimated among and within clusters using MEGA5 (Tamura 
et al
. 2011) and the nuclear 28S gene was examined for fixed differences.

After the removal of primer sequences and ambiguous regions, the 28S alignment (initially 1474 bp) was 1465 bp (99%) and the 16S alignment (initially 515 bp) was 497 bp (97%). The COI alignment was 658 bp. In the alignments, 72 bp of 28S, 69 bp of 16S and 224 bp of COI were informative; the remaining bases were either constant or parsimony uninformative. The model chosen by MrModelTest was GTR+I for 28S, GTR+G for 16S and GTR+I+G for COI. Inspection of the individual gene trees did not reveal any well-supported clades in conflict (
Fig. 1
).

